article.headline: California 71, USC 60
article.story: BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- Leon Powe jumped onto the front row of the California student cheering section and touched more hands than a politician, slapping high-fives and basking in the cheers from another dominant performance. If the Golden Bears' 71-60 victory over USC on Saturday night turns out to be the star sophomore's last campus performance, Powe left a memory for everyone -- even the few fans he didn't personally touch. Powe had 22 points and 11 rebounds to wrap up his Pac-10 titles in both categories as Cal secured the No. 3 seed in next week's conference tournament in Los Angeles, where the Bears (18-9, 12-6) will get a rematch with the fading Trojans in Thursday's quarterfinals. The Bears owe it to Powe, who finished his strong second season in a talent-thin league with more of the pounding inside play that's turned around Cal's basketball fortunes. The win also improved Cal's chances for an NCAA tournament berth -- and that's what was really on Powe's mind. "I want to do some more, but 18-9, I think that's pretty cool," Powe said. "I think we're very close, if not in already. If we get a couple more wins, that'll just assure everything. ... I knew if we lost this (game), we probably weren't going to get in." Cal is near the bubble for its first NCAA tournament bid since 2002, but the Bears seem to be in good shape with their 12 conference victories. No Pac-10 team has missed the tournament with at least 11 conference victories since 1988. Ayinde Ubaka scored 17 points and DeVon Hardin had 10 points and 11 rebounds for the Golden Bears, who jumped to a big second-half lead and made their free throws down the stretch. Cal shook off any hangover from its overtime loss to UCLA on Thursday, ruining the Bears' chance at a conference championship. With the Cal students chanting his name during perhaps his final appearance at Haas Pavilion, Powe clinched the league scoring title after Washington's Brandon Roy, whose 19.7 points-per-game average trailed Powe's 19.9 entering the day, managed just 16 points in the Huskies' win at Arizona. Powe also got his second conference rebounding title after leading the Pac-10 as a freshman in 2003-04. He's just the sixth player to lead the Pac-10 in both categories, the same feat accomplished by Arizona State's Ike Diogu last season. "Leon deserves a lot of the credit for the impact he's made," Cal coach Ben Braun said. "He makes a lot of things easier for a lot of guys. He's also been a really good defender for us this year. he's really improved his understanding of the game." Lodrick Stewart scored 14 of his 16 points in the second half, and Nick Young added 12 points before turning his ankle as the Trojans (17-12, 8-10) finished the regular season with six losses in their last eight games. USC had an awful shooting game, going 11:15 between field goals in the second half of an 18-for-60 performance. The Trojans took 34 3-pointers, mostly because they couldn't do anything inside against the tall Bears. "We just ended up on the outside, and when you do, you've going to have nights when you shoot poorly," USC coach Tim Floyd said. "We've got to learn to run our offense through the post. We just didn't get anything around the basket." After going 8½ minutes without a field goal in the first half, Cal made an 18-4 run in the second half that included points from six players. USC managed nothing but free throws between Stewart's baskets with 16:40 and 5:25 to play, yet still got within 63-54 on Gabe Pruitt's 3-pointer with 1:04 left before Cal finished it. Young and Pruitt, who led last-place USC to an upset win at Cal last season, combined for 9-of-26 shooting. "They're good, and they're too big, and Leon had a great game," Young said after struggling to guard Cal's centers because Floyd wanted to keep his leading scorer out of the foul trouble that's usually caused by guarding Powe. "It's a real tough matchup, me guarding a 7-footer that knows how to play." Richard Midgley, who started his 96th game, and Rod Benson got warm ovations before their final home games, barring an NIT berth. Cal senior walk-on Steve Panawek started the game and returned in the final minute -- and with 5 seconds to play, he got a steal and an awkward breakaway dunk that sent his teammates charging onto the court for hugs and celebrations.
